<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-078-442  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 078 442.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  Jan 15 1990 n283 p16(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Should fiber go to desktops? (the decision has to be made) (lastof a three-part series)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Haight, Timothy.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The decision to wire new buildings with optical fiber in the 1990sneeds to be made now, although opinions vary.andP;  Optical fiber willbe needed for increased video over local area networks and moreimaging applications.andP;  Scanning, facsimile, and optical disktechnology provide ways to enter and archive information cheaply.andO;Video teleconferencing also demands increased bandwidth.andP;  Mostvendors agree that pricing will affect the implementation of fiberand connections for under $500 per node are needed.andP;  At thispoint, planning for uncertainty is the most common strategy.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Fiber OpticsFuture TechnologiesCablesBuilding Management.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>